{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523288","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523288"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:54:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:54:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13888"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13888","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13888"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.5,0.05,0.24,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6505"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92615"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6505","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6505"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13888"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75955"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"165"},{"type":"tags","id":"1307"},{"type":"tags","id":"1366"},{"type":"tags","id":"1627"},{"type":"tags","id":"3565"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12931"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12932"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15475"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30826"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92615","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92615"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with an eight-month history of low back pain, hirsutism, and increasing weight. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears overweight with a pulse rate of 80/min, blood pressure 140/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Her abdomen shows central obesity with purple striae (Image). The patient undergoes a high-dose dexamethasone suppression test which results in adequate suppression of cortisol.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely source of this patient\u0027s pathology?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hypothalamus","Anterior pituitary gland","Posterior pituitary gland","Adrenal gland","Ectopic ACTH-producing tumour"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is consistent with Cushing\u0027s syndrome, characterised by central obesity, hirsutism, and abdominal striae. The key to this diagnosis is the result of the high-dose dexamethasone suppression test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior pituitary gland\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely source of the pathology in this case. Cushing\u0027s disease, caused by an ACTH-secreting pituitary adenoma, is the most common cause of endogenous Cushing\u0027s syndrome. In Cushing\u0027s disease, high doses of dexamethasone can suppress cortisol production because the pituitary tumour retains some sensitivity to negative feedback. This explains the adequate suppression observed in the test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypothalamus\u003C/strong\u003E is not the correct answer as hypothalamic dysfunction would not typically cause this clinical picture or respond to high-dose dexamethasone suppression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior pituitary gland\u003C/strong\u003E does not produce hormones that would cause Cushing\u0027s syndrome, so this option can be ruled out.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eadrenal gland\u003C/strong\u003E tumour causing Cushing\u0027s syndrome would be independent of ACTH and would not be expected to show suppression with high-dose dexamethasone, so this is incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eectopic ACTH-producing tumour\u003C/strong\u003E is typically less responsive to high-dose dexamethasone suppression, so this option can also be ruled out based on the test result.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, the combination of clinical features suggestive of Cushing\u0027s syndrome and adequate suppression with high-dose dexamethasone points to an ACTH-secreting pituitary adenoma (Cushing\u0027s disease) as the most likely diagnosis. The high-dose dexamethasone suppression test is a valuable tool in differentiating between pituitary and non-pituitary sources of ACTH excess in Cushing\u0027s syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cushing\u0027s disease is caused by an ACTH-secreting pituitary adenoma and is the most common cause of endogenous Cushing\u0027s syndrome.","High-dose dexamethasone suppression test helps differentiate sources of ACTH production in Cushing\u0027s syndrome.","Adequate suppression on high-dose dexamethasone suppression test suggests a pituitary source of ACTH excess."],"references":["Prerna Dogra, Vijayashankar NP. Dexamethasone Suppression Test. In: StatPearls [online]. 2019. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK542317/","Fleseriu M, Auchus R, Bancos I, Ben-Shlomo A, Bertherat J, Biermasz NR, et al. Consensus on diagnosis and management of Cushing\u0027s disease: a guideline update. Lancet Diabetes Endocrinol. 2021 Dec;9(12):847-875. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8743006/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75955"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13888"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21789"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21789","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21789"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.co